Description:
[4 bladen][blad 1, recto] Adoration Brussels: The kneeling page on the left, holding a crown in his hands - extremely delicate profile-very much a [onleesbaar] cf. e.g.: Richard II in Wilton triptych [...];
[blad 1, verso] The way he stands comparable to the man in front of the table in January [onleesbaar] of Limburg Chantilly hours [...];
[blad 2, recto] Bruegel: Adoration (Brussels) Date c. 1556? The composition connected with the Vatican tapestries if the same subject, recurs to some extant in the Avaritia of 1556 [...]; [blad 2, verso] point to an earlier date: the earliest figure composition (c. 155?)[sic] after return from Italy [..];
[blad 3, recto] The Negro King and his followers, [...] Also the donkey separated from holy trone (the cow hardly visible - see Brand Philips' interpretation [= Lotte Brand Philip, 'The Prado Epiphany of Jerome Bosch, in: The Art Bulletin, 35 (1953), pp. 267-293] [...]; [blad 3, verso] blanco;
[blad 4, recto] Adoration, Brussels, Ad [Addendum] centralised composition with crowds: perhaps there was a picture of this kind by Bosch - if one can go by the fragments at Philadelphia (right wing, Tolnay, pl. 117b)[...]; Anderlecht altar repr. in J. Leymarie, Bosch [= Jean Leymarie, Jérome Bosch, Paris: Aimery Somogy, 1949] (pl. 88-90) adest; [blad 4, verso] blanco.[scan]

Keyword: Anderlecht, Sint Pieter- en Sint Guidokerk
Rome, Vaticaanstad, Monumenti, Musei e Gallerie Pontificie
